### Phase 1 — Test adequacy
- Migration smoke (3/3) → does it test upgrade + downgrade + head uniqueness?
- F003 test (test_sorted_by_sort_field) → does it test the actual ordering behavior, with reverse-order fixture + exact sequence assert?
- For each test, ask: would deleting the implementation cause the test to fail? (anti-tautology check)
- Are there test gaps (e.g., dialect-neutrality regression test that runs on both SQLite + PG)?

### Phase 2 — Behavioral correctness
- For each migration change: PG semantics preserved? (UniqueConstraint inline ≡ ALTER ADD CONSTRAINT in PG; batch_alter_table ≡ direct ALTER in PG)
- F002 mounting: any side effects on /api/v1/conduct/* routing, ModuleCheckMiddleware, RBAC?
- F003 service: any caller depending on unsorted result?
- Boundary conditions: empty migration, single-item ordering, NULL sort, etc.
- Root cause quality (F001): does the diagnosis pinpoint the dialect issue (not symptom)?
- Scope check (F001): same-pattern (other migrations) / same-boundary (alembic dir only) / same-invariant (INV-04) — all covered?
- Regression risk: does the F002 acknowledgment break any conduct module test? Does the F001 fix affect any deployed PG data?

### Phase 3 — Untested risks
- Migration replay risk on existing PG: zero (claimed). Verify by checking alembic_version table behavior — alembic does not replay applied migrations.
- Concurrent migration in CI: any race? (multiple test workers)
- Migration ordering: does any down_revision or revision ID change? (it should NOT — verify revision graph integrity)
- F002: 28 conduct endpoints — any unauthenticated route, missing scope filter, etc?

